04075nam a22005895i 9780822378266DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20132013ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223782667 a10.1515/97808223782662doi  a(DE-B1597)552335  a(OCoLC)861639469  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aPHO0100002bisacsh04a770.9  aAP 945002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/8151:1 aSmith, Shawn Michelle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAt the Edge of Sight :bPhotography and the Unseen /cShawn Michelle Smith. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b120 photos, incl. 9 in color  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction First Photographs -- tChapter 1 Race and Reproduction in Camera Lucida -- tChapter 2 The Politics of Pictorialism -- t— My Muybridge -- tChapter 3 The Sp ace Between -- tChapter 4 Preparing the Way for the Train -- t— When the Train Rolls In -- tChapter 5 Chansonetta Stanley Emmons’s Nostalgic Views -- tChapter 6 Augustus Washington and the Civil Contract of Photography -- tChapter 7 Afterimages: Abu Ghraib -- t— Untitled (Abu Ghraib) -- tEpilogue A Parting Glance -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe advent of photography revolutionized perception, making visible what was once impossible to see with the human eye. In At the Edge of Sight, Shawn Michelle Smith engages these dynamics of seeing and not seeing, focusing attention as much on absence as presence, on the invisible as the visible. Exploring the limits of photography and vision, she asks: What fails to register photographically, and what remains beyond the frame? What is hidden by design, and what is obscured by cultural blindness? Smith studies manifestations of photography's brush with the unseen in her own photographic work and across the wide-ranging images of early American photographers, including F. Holland Day, Eadweard Muybridge, Andrew J. Russell, Chansonetta Stanley Emmons, and Augustus Washington. She concludes by showing how concerns raised in the nineteenth century remain pertinent today in the photographs of Abu Ghraib. Ultimately, Smith explores the capacity of photography to reveal what remains beyond the edge of sight.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aPhotographyxHistoryxUnited States. 0aPhotographyxSocial aspectsxUnited States. 0aPhotographyxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aPhotographyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPhotography, ArtisticxHistory. 7aPhotography / History.2bisacsh1 aRussell, Andrew J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822378266zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822378266423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822378266/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles